WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
Julia is a data scientist and engineering manager at PositPVC, where she leads a team

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:15.600
of developers building fluent, cohesive, open-source software for data science and Python and R.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:19.799
She's a tool builder, author, international keynote speaker, and real-world data science

00:00:19.799 --> 00:00:20.799
practitioner.

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:24.760
She holds a PhD in astrophysics and serves on the Technical Advisory Committee of the

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.760
U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:32.759
You can find her online on her blog, which is quite excellent, and YouTube.

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:37.759
Thank you so much, Julie.

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:40.840
Great.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:45.240
I am super happy to be here at what is my first SciPy.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:50.040
I've had multiple people that I have worked with tell me it is their favorite conference,

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:56.040
so I'm really happy to be able to be here and join you today and to speak specifically

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:03.200
about the process of using multiple programming languages for scientific computing and how

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:09.120
we can explore or start to identify what is the right tool for the job.

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:14.440
Before I get a little deeper into it, I want to tell you a little bit about the path that

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:20.160
brought me here to be standing in front of all of you talking about this.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:26.320
My academic background is in physics and astronomy, but I came up through those fields

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:32.599
before the dominance of Python in these fields and in scientific computing in general.

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:38.800
If I were maybe 5 to 10 years younger than I am, the tooling that we are all here to

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:46.279
talk about would be my tooling, and you would be my people, but I started in these fields

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:52.279
before that era, and so I and the people around me when I was in academic departments doing

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:57.599
physics and astronomy, we wrote a lot of C. We wrote a lot of FORTRAN.

00:01:57.599 --> 00:02:03.400
We wrote a lot of bespoke code that in hindsight really does make a lot more sense to have

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:08.619
in a well-maintained community resource like AstroPy and that whole ecosystem.

00:02:08.619 --> 00:02:13.800
There were people around me who wrote IRAF, who used IRAF and IDL, closed source tools

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:14.679
like that.

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:21.399
This was like my first scientific computing experience, my first exposure to how to use

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:24.759
computing for scientific purposes.

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:31.320
So I was in academia for a while, left, did a few pretty random things in tech companies

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:37.399
for a little while, and about 10 years ago made a career transition, made a change in

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:44.360
my professional identity to the sort of at the time newly burgeoning field of data science.

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:46.080
So I became a data scientist.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:52.360
As I made this transition, I brought with me my excellent quantitative training that

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:56.559
came from being someone who studied physics and astronomy.

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:03.000
I brought with me a lot of real-world experience dealing with data, messy data that I collected

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:10.080
myself at telescopes, a lot of experience understanding how can I know what kinds of

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:12.399
questions I can answer with this data?

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:17.559
How can I communicate about this data with data visualization and speaking and writing?

00:03:17.559 --> 00:03:24.119
However, I did not know at the time modern data science languages, and so as I was making

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:29.279
this transition, it was my first time really wrestling with, is it worth it?

00:03:29.279 --> 00:03:30.639
Do I need to do this?

00:03:30.639 --> 00:03:34.080
Is this important for me to add additional languages?

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:41.759
So I first learned Python, and I then learned R, and actually it turns out R has proven

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:47.679
to be one of the great loves of my professional life, and my exposure to R was such a good

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:55.080
fit for how I approached data analysis that it really had a huge impact on how my career

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:57.160
then went after that.

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:03.639
The work that I'm probably most strongly associated with is my open source, my work in the R world

00:04:03.639 --> 00:04:08.559
in open source and books and learning materials and that kind of thing.

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:10.199
So I moved into data science.

00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:16.480
I was a data science practitioner, and I started being involved with tool building on the side.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:21.399
I bet as many of you are, you have one sort of day job, and then you contribute to open

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:24.519
source on the side in your own time.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:30.760
About four, four and a half years ago, I made a bit of a pivot again to becoming a full-time

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:36.079
tool builder, so spending all my time building tools for data science.

00:04:36.079 --> 00:04:41.160
So when this pivot happened, this was me changing my job from working in tech as a

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:46.760
data scientist to working at a company that was then called RStudio.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:52.079
So I started working at RStudio and started working on open source software for machine

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:55.239
learning, for text analysis.

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:59.640
Now about the company that I work for, it's the same company, but it's no longer called

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:00.640
that.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.519
So the company that I work for is now called Posit.

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:12.320
The main motivation for this rebrand or rename is that for a long time, the company that

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:21.600
I work for has built software, tools for scientific computing, for data science, that are tools

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:27.359
for Python, that are tools for R, of course, that are tools for Julia.

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:30.359
It's actually, people don't believe you, honestly.

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:35.000
When you say that, when your name is so strongly associated with one particular programming

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:36.279
language.

00:05:36.279 --> 00:05:41.399
So we rebranded, we made this new name to try to be more clear about who we are.

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:46.760
And now when I think about what I spend my time doing and what I see the people around

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:52.440
me who I work with, what we spend our time doing, I notice that we now have, you know,

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:58.359
in aggregate, like years of experience building tools using multiple programming languages.

00:05:58.359 --> 00:06:02.920
So they use multiple programming languages in two ways.

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:09.399
First, we ourselves internally use multiple languages as we build these tools.

00:06:09.399 --> 00:06:14.679
You know, my company is probably best known for the RStudio IDE, and if you go to GitHub

00:06:14.679 --> 00:06:20.839
and you look at the GitHub repo for the RStudio IDE, you can see actually the pretty long

00:06:20.839 --> 00:06:23.760
list of languages that are used to build that.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:30.600
So we internally as an org have experience needing to use multiple languages together

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:34.040
as we collaborate to build the tools that we're building.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:39.519
We also have years of experience building tools for multiple programming languages because

00:06:39.519 --> 00:06:44.559
the tools we build are meant to be used from multiple programming languages.

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:51.559
So I'm going to share a couple of examples of these that I'll use to illustrate the points

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:52.720
as we go along.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:55.519
So the first one I want to talk about is Cordo.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:07:03.720
So Cordo is a tool for scientific authoring documents that can be used from Python, R,

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:04.720
Julia.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:05.720
It works with Observable.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:13.000
So it's a tool that you can use to write a paper or to make a website or to make package

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.839
documentation or to make slides, actually.

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:19.799
The slides that you're looking at are, in fact, created with Cordo, and they're available

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:24.160
at that URL down at the bottom if you'd like to check them out afterwards.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:29.880
If you were here on Monday, you may have had the opportunity to go to a tutorial to be

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:34.600
able to learn how to use Cordo for scientific communication in Python.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:40.679
Another one is Shiny, which is a tool for making interactive apps for data, and Shiny

00:07:40.679 --> 00:07:45.160
has an implementation in Python and an implementation in R.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:49.700
We at Posit, there are folks who work on tools for making publication-ready tables.

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:54.420
So if you need a table in a paper you're writing or for the website that you're making,

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:58.660
and Great Tables is a tool for Python and for R.

00:07:58.660 --> 00:08:02.700
And later in the conference, tomorrow, I believe, there's actually a talk here about how to

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:08.260
use the Great Tables Python packaging for creating beautiful tables that you need.

00:08:08.260 --> 00:08:15.739
So these are all examples of things of which I am a user, but not directly a developer.

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:22.380
And then this next set are ones that I myself have been involved directly in working on

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:28.059
and really inform how I think about these issues of using multiple languages.

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:29.739
The first is Vetiver.

00:08:29.739 --> 00:08:34.219
So Vetiver is software in Python and R for MLOps.

00:08:34.219 --> 00:08:41.820
Pins is software in Python and R for versioning, publishing, and sharing data.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:47.380
And then I'm excited to also share some new work that I've been working on recently with

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:48.799
folks here.

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:51.859
So these are all sort of the, this is the context, right?

00:08:51.859 --> 00:09:01.940
Like the context for what are the experiences that have brought me to think about what's

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:03.419
hard and what's easy?

00:09:03.419 --> 00:09:07.219
And what are the things that come up when we use multiple programming languages?

00:09:07.219 --> 00:09:11.340
As I thought about, as I was thinking about standing here in front of you and talking

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:15.099
to you all, like what do I want to talk about with the people at SciPy?

00:09:15.099 --> 00:09:17.940
What do I feel like I've noticed or learned?

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:23.619
There are three things, three things that I want for us to talk about here together.

00:09:23.619 --> 00:09:29.659
The first is what does it cost when we use multiple programming languages in scientific

00:09:29.659 --> 00:09:31.460
computing context?

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:37.500
The second is what do we gain when we start using these different programming languages?

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:43.059
And when we have curiosity and openness to different ways of doing things, what does

00:09:43.059 --> 00:09:48.820
that allow us to share or to give to the people around us or to the communities around us?

00:09:48.820 --> 00:09:50.580
So let's dig in.

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:54.440
Let's dig into this first one and let's talk about cost.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:10:01.260
So what if, hypothetically, I stood in front of you and I said, you really need to learn

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:03.419
another programming language?

00:10:03.419 --> 00:10:04.419
I'm not.

00:10:04.419 --> 00:10:05.419
To be clear, I am not saying that.

00:10:05.419 --> 00:10:06.419
I am not saying that.

00:10:06.419 --> 00:10:09.299
But what, like, hypothetically, imagine how you would feel, you know?

00:10:09.299 --> 00:10:15.239
And I think that many of you probably, like, you would feel a reaction.

00:10:15.239 --> 00:10:17.320
You would feel like maybe a defensiveness.

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:22.619
You might feel a certain sense of I'm absolutely not going to do that or, like, I don't have

00:10:22.619 --> 00:10:24.380
the time to do that.

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:30.739
That's because there are huge costs associated with learning new programming languages.

00:10:30.739 --> 00:10:32.500
It's really expensive.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:37.859
It's expensive in terms of time, energy, concentration, effort.

00:10:37.859 --> 00:10:43.859
It takes a lot to learn, especially if we're talking about becoming professionally competent

00:10:43.859 --> 00:10:46.099
in an additional programming language.

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:50.419
This is something I myself have done several times through my career, and so I'm very familiar

00:10:50.419 --> 00:10:54.739
with, like, how challenging it can be and how costly.

00:10:54.739 --> 00:11:00.820
I do think these costs, you know, may be changing a little bit in the era of LLM-based

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:02.500
coding assistant tools.

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:08.299
This is an area, like, I've actually seen them work be quite helpful to people, like,

00:11:08.299 --> 00:11:13.380
maybe when they know one programming language and then are, you know, want to translate

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:17.260
something to another language or learning a new language and are asking, like, hey,

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:20.219
how do I do this but in this other language?

00:11:20.219 --> 00:11:25.659
But, you know, nothing that I've seen from these type of LLM-based tools really changes

00:11:25.659 --> 00:11:33.580
the fundamental fact of how expensive it is for a person to gain competency in a new entire

00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:35.380
programming language.

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:39.820
At the same time, there are real benefits to specialization.

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:45.179
If you yourself probably have experienced this in your career, like, you have had good

00:11:45.179 --> 00:11:50.059
things happen to you because of the way that you have specialized in something, or when

00:11:50.059 --> 00:11:54.539
you build a partnership or a collaboration with someone, you know, often you don't want

00:11:54.539 --> 00:11:59.260
to have exact overlap in the kinds of skills that you and the other person have, but instead

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:04.419
you want your skills to be complementary to another person's skills, so it's not perfect

00:12:04.419 --> 00:12:06.780
overlap but complementary overlap.

00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:08.460
So these are real.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:13.739
The costs of learning, the benefits of specialization are really real.

00:12:13.739 --> 00:12:17.780
So this is what we kind of experience at the individual level, and when we think about

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:22.820
the organization level, these costs kind of get aggregated up, and so if you have everyone

00:12:22.820 --> 00:12:27.099
in an organization starting to experience these kinds of costs, you start to observe

00:12:27.099 --> 00:12:31.539
tension and problems around consistency and complexity.

00:12:31.539 --> 00:12:37.179
So consistency, you know, gets pushed down, and complexity gets pushed up, and, you know,

00:12:37.179 --> 00:12:43.380
we start to have questions like, well, who can do code review for this other person if

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:46.739
we don't have someone who knows that programming language?

00:12:46.739 --> 00:12:51.580
Or, well, if we have multiple ways of building a model, like, how are we going to go about

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.419
deploying these different kinds of models?

00:12:54.419 --> 00:13:01.260
And these experiences, which are real, right, these experiences that I bet many of us have

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:07.739
observed or experienced the way I have, they result in people having a belief or a value

00:13:07.739 --> 00:13:10.580
that you might express like this.

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:15.059
There should be one, and preferably only one, obvious way to do it.

00:13:15.059 --> 00:13:20.099
This comes from the Zen of Python, and this is a statement that is saying, like, it's

00:13:20.099 --> 00:13:22.419
really important for us to be consistent.

00:13:22.419 --> 00:13:27.700
It's really important for us to not have unneeded complexity here.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:31.500
And I, like, I have experienced these kinds of costs firsthand.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:35.179
An example that comes to mind for this is my work on the pins package.

00:13:35.179 --> 00:13:42.419
So pins is software in Python and R for versioning, publishing, and sharing data.

00:13:42.419 --> 00:13:49.340
And it, the example here, this slide shows you how you might write a pin to a board.

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:52.539
The sort of metaphor here is that you have, there's a pin board somewhere, and you're

00:13:52.539 --> 00:13:57.460
pinning things on it, and versioning, there's nice support for getting versions of different

00:13:57.460 --> 00:14:03.619
datasets, and you can, you know, be specified, for example, here, we're going to write something

00:14:03.619 --> 00:14:04.619
as a parquet file.

00:14:05.059 --> 00:14:08.260
So this is what writing looks like, this is what reading looks like.

00:14:08.260 --> 00:14:14.299
And the, I'm using a toy dummy board here, but in real life, you would use a board that

00:14:14.299 --> 00:14:20.619
is like an S3 bucket, or a network drive on a high-performance computing cluster, or,

00:14:20.619 --> 00:14:27.140
you know, Google Cloud Storage, or whatever, and pins is like a friendly user interface

00:14:27.140 --> 00:14:32.500
for a data science user persona, a data analyst user persona, so that they don't have to,

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:37.580
they can, you can switch out back ends in a pretty flexible way and not get, you know,

00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:42.299
dragged down in the specifics of how things have to be versioned on an S3 bucket versus

00:14:42.299 --> 00:14:46.580
another kind of, another kind of way of storing data.

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:51.659
Okay, so reading and writing data, you know, and it is explicitly, like a goal of pins

00:14:51.659 --> 00:14:59.700
is to support interoperability, but we, we observe that there is cost for individuals

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:00.940
when they need to do this.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:07.900
So in the slide, I showed writing using Parquet, and Parquet has really, really great features

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:09.380
around interoperability.

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:14.940
You can read and write Parquet files from Python, and R, and JavaScript, and C, and

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:18.900
like all, like all these different ways of reading and writing and getting consistent

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:19.900
results.

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:24.739
Like that's, that is a point, a whole point of Parquet and Arrow.

00:15:24.739 --> 00:15:31.140
If you, if you know that already, that's fantastic, and you are set up for success.

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:36.780
However, there are stumbling blocks that people kind of hit when they, when they don't have,

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:41.739
they have not yet engaged, spent the cost to, to learn what they'll need to do to like

00:15:41.739 --> 00:15:42.739
really collaborate.

00:15:42.739 --> 00:15:47.299
And honestly, this even comes up with things like trying to store things as CSV, which

00:15:47.299 --> 00:15:51.780
you may think is just like, you know, this is plain text, but you can run into problems

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:57.940
trying to read and write CSVs from, from Python to other languages, like to R. And,

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:02.859
and then, you know, there's just a whole universe of binary for file maps that are quite difficult

00:16:02.859 --> 00:16:05.900
to open in versus one language versus the other.

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:10.900
So this, so there, if a individual wants to have this kind of collaboration with someone

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:14.700
who uses a different programming language for them, they have to face this.

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:20.179
They have to face and, and spend, spend this energy and time to get it right.

00:16:20.179 --> 00:16:23.419
We also have observed cost to our organization.

00:16:23.419 --> 00:16:30.500
So the, so the pins, Python package and R package are explicitly built to work together.

00:16:30.500 --> 00:16:38.619
But what that means is that the steps we take to, to write tests, to run those tests on,

00:16:38.619 --> 00:16:46.119
on a CI system, like we have to scale up the complexity of those projects because interoperability

00:16:46.119 --> 00:16:48.159
is an explicit goal of them.

00:16:48.159 --> 00:16:53.239
So if someone is only an expert in, say, Python packaging, they have to, like, there's

00:16:53.239 --> 00:16:58.159
a cost in that person having to think, OK, I need to also learn about R packaging.

00:16:58.159 --> 00:17:02.559
I need to also learn about how GitHub actions works for R in a different, in addition to

00:17:02.559 --> 00:17:05.439
how GitHub actions work for Python.

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:06.640
So these costs are real.

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:10.920
And I certainly could not stand in front of you with any credibility and talk about using

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:15.439
multiple programming languages without, without starting here, without acknowledging them

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:21.319
and kind of outlining the specifics of the ways that these, these costs come up.

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:27.239
I am now going to, and to start and talking about what is it that we gain when we use

00:17:27.239 --> 00:17:29.280
multiple programming languages.

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:35.400
And I am going to start back at the organization level because I know that's top of mind when

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:42.040
people try to think about, oh, like, will we support using XYZ language in our research

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:44.760
group or company or department?

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:51.959
So the, at any given time, the people that are in your organization are better at some

00:17:51.959 --> 00:17:57.939
task using one, one tool versus another tool.

00:17:57.939 --> 00:18:03.920
And when that person can make the choice of what tool they're going to use, they are,

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:05.479
they are going to be more productive.

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:11.400
And so when we use multiple programming languages, this makes, this makes everybody more productive.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:21.199
But this, this dynamic is in tension with the consistency, consistency, complexity thing,

00:18:21.199 --> 00:18:25.160
like, like, oh, we're having problems around consistency and complexity.

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:30.219
This ends up, this ends up being intention or balancing everyone actually being better

00:18:30.219 --> 00:18:32.760
at the work that they are trying to do.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:38.359
And in my experience, like there is no a priori way of knowing how that balance is going to

00:18:38.359 --> 00:18:39.359
play out.

00:18:39.359 --> 00:18:46.239
Like there is, there's no hard and fast rule about how, like which one of those will win

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:47.239
in the end.

00:18:47.239 --> 00:18:53.239
It depends on scale of your, you know, it depends on the, like the specifics of what

00:18:53.239 --> 00:18:55.520
the infrastructure is like in your organization.

00:18:55.520 --> 00:19:00.920
There's these things are intention, but they, they, it is not necessarily true that one

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:03.719
always wins versus the other.

00:19:03.719 --> 00:19:07.839
This leading to people to just be like, okay, well, let's figure it out.

00:19:07.839 --> 00:19:12.800
Let's take a pragmatic attitude to how it is that we, how we choose tools.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:18.319
This leads to like a belief or a value that you might express like this, practicality

00:19:18.319 --> 00:19:19.319
beats purity.

00:19:19.319 --> 00:19:25.079
This is also from the Zen of Python, and this is a, this is a, like a reflection of the

00:19:25.079 --> 00:19:34.560
idea that we can, we can, we can in our specific circumstances decide what works best at this

00:19:34.560 --> 00:19:39.760
point and not have an overly purist view about tooling or how people should be doing

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:40.760
things.

00:19:40.760 --> 00:19:44.560
This is really related to this idea of the right tool for the job.

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:51.680
And what I observe is that it is, it is very difficult and, you know, like maybe plain

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:58.079
impossible to make, to make overarching general statements about what a right tool for a job

00:19:58.079 --> 00:19:59.079
is.

00:19:59.079 --> 00:20:04.560
But instead, what the right tool for the job is, is always specific to a circumstance,

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.959
to a person, even to a time.

00:20:06.959 --> 00:20:11.280
So the right question isn't what is the right tool for the job, but what is the right tool

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:16.239
for the job for this person at this time in this organization?

00:20:16.239 --> 00:20:21.880
The project that I worked on that, where I've seen this play out a lot is, is, is Vetiver.

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:27.280
So Vetiver is software for Python and R that, for MLOps.

00:20:27.280 --> 00:20:32.719
So for about the, the process of deploying and operationalizing models.

00:20:32.719 --> 00:20:36.199
So the, when you say MLOps, people mean a lot of different things.

00:20:36.199 --> 00:20:41.280
So I'm going to get a little specific here by looking at this diagram of a model lifecycle.

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:45.959
So if we start with, you know, we start by collecting data.

00:20:45.959 --> 00:20:49.920
The first thing we'll need to do when we have that data is to understand and clean it.

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:55.719
And there's lots of great open source software, open source tools for understanding and cleaning

00:20:55.719 --> 00:20:56.719
your data.

00:20:56.719 --> 00:21:01.079
Next, the next thing you do is it's time to train and evaluate a machine learning model.

00:21:01.079 --> 00:21:07.119
And again, there's lots of really fantastic open source packages across different languages

00:21:07.119 --> 00:21:11.359
to, to train and evaluate the model.

00:21:11.359 --> 00:21:15.520
At that point, it, the situation becomes much less clear.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:22.439
And that's both because there, there's a lot less community understanding of what, what

00:21:22.439 --> 00:21:26.760
is the right next thing to do once you have a machine learning model trained.

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:32.760
And also because there are fewer open source tools for what needs to happen next.

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:38.839
Especially fewer open source tools built for a scientist, data analyst, data scientist

00:21:38.839 --> 00:21:44.239
type user, as opposed to what I might call a generalist software engineer type user.

00:21:44.239 --> 00:21:46.119
And this is where Vetiver sits.

00:21:46.119 --> 00:21:51.400
Vetiver has a opinionated idea of what are the next things you need to do.

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:55.400
You need to version your model, deploy your model, and then monitor your model.

00:21:55.400 --> 00:22:00.760
And also provides, provides functions and infrastructure for, for taking those next

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:01.760
steps.

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:08.599
And it's really about this, like giving people the opportunity to choose the right tool for,

00:22:08.599 --> 00:22:09.880
for what they are needing to do.

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:15.359
So person A might decide, oh, I'm going to train a random forest model using Scikit-learn

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:16.640
and Python.

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:21.800
And they can deploy, they can version, deploy, and monitor their model with Vetiver.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:27.199
And person B might say, oh, I need to create a survival analysis model.

00:22:27.199 --> 00:22:31.839
And I think the best way to do that is going to be to use tidy models and R. And they also

00:22:31.839 --> 00:22:37.680
can use Vetiver to, to version, deploy, and monitor their model.

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:44.400
So the, the, what, one thing I really have observed with our, our users of Vetiver, people

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:51.079
telling us about how they're using it, is that it allows people to have autonomy to

00:22:51.079 --> 00:22:56.000
make the best decisions, giving their own domain knowledge about what they know, what

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.520
they know about their data and their situation.

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:01.959
And still actually get back some of that consistency.

00:23:01.959 --> 00:23:08.719
Like we can, and tools themselves can be designed in such a way so that we can give people the

00:23:08.719 --> 00:23:14.160
flexibility that increases their production, allows them to make the best decision in the

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:19.640
context in which they are working, and also push back against these problems around a

00:23:19.640 --> 00:23:25.160
consistency and a complexity that arise when people do things in different ways.

00:23:25.160 --> 00:23:30.760
And just to, just to maybe lay this out a little bit more in detail, the, these are

00:23:30.760 --> 00:23:35.040
the sort of opinionated tasks that Vetiver says, this is what needs to happen to your,

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:39.119
your model after you have, after you have decided this is the model for me.

00:23:39.119 --> 00:23:41.359
I have, I have created it.

00:23:41.359 --> 00:23:46.640
These tasks, these like jobs to be done, are not about whether someone is trying to

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:50.880
do them in Python or R or some other language.

00:23:50.880 --> 00:23:55.319
They are at the same time kind of more concrete and more abstract.

00:23:55.319 --> 00:24:00.660
And by more concrete, I mean there's really lower level technologies at play here.

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:06.479
Things like REST API, things like I need to pass JSON back and forth over, you know, over

00:24:06.479 --> 00:24:07.599
an API call.

00:24:07.599 --> 00:24:09.680
And at the same time, they're also more abstract.

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:14.119
Like they're, like, they're like, I need to, I need to monitor my model, you know,

00:24:14.119 --> 00:24:16.199
like that's a more abstract thing.

00:24:16.199 --> 00:24:24.520
And it is possible to design, to design tools for people doing scientific computing that

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:32.400
provide more consistency in their user-facing API so that we can, we can design for the

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:37.280
jobs that need to be done and provide this, more of this flexibility and autonomy for

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:40.119
people as they're choosing their tools.

00:24:40.119 --> 00:24:44.520
Now that is, that's at the organization level, right?

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:51.000
Like what is it that we end up gaining when we make, when, how people become more productive?

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:52.319
And let's go back to the individual.

00:24:52.319 --> 00:24:58.520
And again, hypothetically, hypothetically, what if I stood up here and said, you need

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:03.040
to learn another programming language, which again, to be clear, I absolutely am not.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:06.560
But like I want to reflect on what happens when people do.

00:25:06.560 --> 00:25:15.000
What happens when people do take opportunities as they come and, and, and add other things,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.800
other languages to their toolkit?

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:23.000
What are the things, the benefits that individuals gain and, and, and observe?

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.599
The first one is that people scale their impact.

00:25:26.599 --> 00:25:32.520
If you are someone who can solve a certain problem using a certain toolkit, that's great.

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:37.880
But if you are someone who can see a problem and understand different ways of solving it,

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:44.400
weigh pros and cons that are specific to your situation, understand how certain stacks connect

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:50.920
into other infrastructure, understand like how, how that systems level thinking about

00:25:50.920 --> 00:25:58.199
a problem, that second person has much more impact in their field, in their organization,

00:25:58.199 --> 00:26:02.800
in their, in the areas in which they work.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:07.719
We also, I think it's important to think about the long term when it comes to these kinds

00:26:07.719 --> 00:26:10.959
of, these kinds of like issues that are individual.

00:26:10.959 --> 00:26:17.479
I do know some people who have spent their whole career using one programming language

00:26:17.479 --> 00:26:20.920
and are really happy and fulfilled and successful.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:23.599
But in my experience, that's, that's fairly rare.

00:26:23.599 --> 00:26:24.599
That's fairly rare.

00:26:24.599 --> 00:26:30.359
You know, a lot of us at least also use SQL, right, like in addition to the other languages

00:26:30.359 --> 00:26:31.359
that we use.

00:26:31.359 --> 00:26:37.439
But I also observe some, I'm going to call them like archetypal arcs, career arcs that

00:26:37.439 --> 00:26:42.520
people often take that as they consider what do they want to do with their career in the

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:43.680
long term.

00:26:43.680 --> 00:26:48.599
A common arc I observe is people starting from high level scripting languages like Python

00:26:48.599 --> 00:26:54.000
and R and moving to the front end, like really becoming experts in JavaScript.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:59.880
And often this is people who are really interested in data visualization or making interactive

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:01.719
apps and dashboards.

00:27:01.719 --> 00:27:04.319
I observe people, you know, kind of going the other way.

00:27:04.319 --> 00:27:08.479
They will start with a high level scripting language like Python or R and then move lower

00:27:08.479 --> 00:27:12.780
level to use something like Rust or C or Go.

00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:18.160
Often these are people who are working on, you know, mathematical methods, machine learning

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:22.959
methods, people who are building developer tooling so that you, you know, we have to

00:27:22.959 --> 00:27:28.280
work at the, at a lower level because maybe the high level scripting language needs to

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.680
talk to something else and so we need to work at a lower level.

00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:36.319
My own arc, I don't know, I perceive it to be a little weird, right?

00:27:36.319 --> 00:27:40.920
Like I started a long time ago with C, I went way to the front end, I was actually paid

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:43.280
to write Flash for a little bit, believe it or not.

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:48.280
And then like I landed back kind of in this, at the high level scripting language layer,

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:49.640
building tools for this layer.

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:55.359
But I think it, like when we can have a long-term view of what our careers are like, we can

00:27:55.359 --> 00:28:00.760
better understand, more accurately understand what the individual benefits are and whether

00:28:00.760 --> 00:28:06.400
it's worth it at any given time to learn something else.

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:12.119
And the last thing I want to say here about what individuals gain is about increasing

00:28:12.119 --> 00:28:14.479
your vocabulary.

00:28:14.479 --> 00:28:19.680
So the metaphor here is from natural human language, like different languages that we

00:28:19.680 --> 00:28:20.680
use.

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:26.680
If you yourself are bilingual or if you've, you know, dabbled in other languages or, you

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:31.640
know, you hear about people learning languages, you probably have come up, will come up against

00:28:31.640 --> 00:28:39.000
some situation where there's a word that, no, there's a word that correctly, so perfectly

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:45.680
expresses some concept in one language only, or not in another language.

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:49.400
And you know, we might say like, oh, it's very difficult to translate that word because

00:28:49.400 --> 00:28:53.400
of how a word is connected to some concept.

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:59.280
And you know, people might use that word in, when they're speaking in other languages,

00:28:59.280 --> 00:29:03.760
because it's so perfectly encapsulates some concept.

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:05.959
This happens in computing.

00:29:05.959 --> 00:29:09.719
Computing languages are really different from each other and are built with different

00:29:09.719 --> 00:29:13.359
priorities, really different characteristics.

00:29:13.359 --> 00:29:21.040
And sometimes some concept in computing is really well expressed in one language.

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:26.359
And it, you know, maybe cannot be translated or cannot be translated perfectly to some

00:29:26.359 --> 00:29:27.880
other language.

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:34.400
When we have curiosity and openness to things that are happening, you know, a little bit

00:29:34.439 --> 00:29:40.839
outside our own communities, that allows us to increase the vocabulary of what we understand

00:29:40.839 --> 00:29:43.359
we can do using scientific computing.

00:29:43.359 --> 00:29:46.319
Okay, so we talked about cost.

00:29:46.319 --> 00:29:47.599
We talked about what we gain.

00:29:47.599 --> 00:29:53.920
And now I want to talk about what using multiple programming languages allows us to share or

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:59.119
to give across both to individuals and to different communities.

00:29:59.119 --> 00:30:06.520
And I approach this question mostly as a tool builder, because it is in the process

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:12.760
of building tools that I have most observed this phenomenon of someone learning from one

00:30:12.760 --> 00:30:17.640
community and then bringing that thing that they've learned to another community.

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:20.439
So let me be a little concrete about what this might look like.

00:30:20.439 --> 00:30:29.079
So the main R package documentation generation tool is called Roxygen.

00:30:29.079 --> 00:30:35.079
And it is pretty directly inspired by the Doxygen tool to create docs that I bet many

00:30:35.079 --> 00:30:38.760
of you have run into or seen or experienced.

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:44.079
R as a programming language does not have interpolated string literals.

00:30:44.079 --> 00:30:49.760
And people inside the R community observed how great that is, like in Python or TypeScript

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:50.760
or other languages.

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:56.000
And they're like, let's bring that great idea of interpolated string literals to R.

00:30:56.079 --> 00:31:02.920
So they built a tool called Glue that gives you that kind of behavior for strings.

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:05.920
So those are both examples of things coming to R.

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:12.079
But of course, this moves around in all kinds of directions all the time.

00:31:12.079 --> 00:31:18.599
I'm going to highlight Cordo here again, because Cordo is a next generation implementation

00:31:18.599 --> 00:31:23.380
of a kind of working, a way of working that did come from the R community.

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:27.020
So the original implementation was called R Markdown.

00:31:27.020 --> 00:31:31.839
And it is a plain, it's like some of the main characteristics of it are plain text format.

00:31:31.839 --> 00:31:38.979
So that's in contrast to a Jupyter Notebook, interspersed plain text and executable code

00:31:38.979 --> 00:31:39.979
chunks.

00:31:39.979 --> 00:31:45.619
And in the R community, R Markdown was so life changing, like so impactful for people

00:31:45.619 --> 00:31:50.540
as they worked, that it motivated, like, let's build this tool in a way so that it's not

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:55.819
specific to R, but actually can be applied to different kinds of computing languages.

00:31:55.819 --> 00:31:58.380
And can be used for all kinds of different purposes.

00:31:58.380 --> 00:32:01.579
Like I use Cordo to write my blog.

00:32:01.579 --> 00:32:04.060
I use Cordo to make my slides.

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:12.140
And you can do this from Python, R, Julia, like all these different ways of using this.

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:16.579
So there's all these examples of things moving around all the time.

00:32:16.579 --> 00:32:22.140
Looking at the company I do, like the company RStudio, if you think about this idea of,

00:32:22.140 --> 00:32:25.020
like, oh, something is great in one community.

00:32:25.020 --> 00:32:27.339
How can we take it somewhere else?

00:32:27.339 --> 00:32:31.140
I will say there's one thing that's top of mind for people.

00:32:31.140 --> 00:32:38.380
People will say things like, gosh, is there anything like RStudio but for Python?

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:40.500
Or they're like, hey, I'm loving Python.

00:32:40.500 --> 00:32:46.459
Python is, like, really fun and I'm loving it, but I still prefer RStudio as an IDE.

00:32:46.459 --> 00:32:52.180
Or people will say, oh, we have there are these certain features that are out there

00:32:52.180 --> 00:32:58.060
that are in the RStudio IDE and I really want that feature, but when I do my Python work.

00:32:58.060 --> 00:33:00.140
Or people will say this to us.

00:33:00.140 --> 00:33:03.260
All I want is PyStudio.

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:08.579
So I am really excited to announce the project that I have been spending a lot of time over

00:33:08.579 --> 00:33:13.099
the last year, and that is a brand new data science IDE.

00:33:13.099 --> 00:33:16.380
So this data science IDE is called Positron.

00:33:16.380 --> 00:33:22.140
And if you have ever used RStudio or seen somebody use RStudio, a lot of this looks

00:33:22.140 --> 00:33:23.260
familiar.

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:26.380
There is a pane where you write your source code.

00:33:26.380 --> 00:33:33.300
There is a truly interactive console, like, fully featured interactive console.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:39.140
There's UI affordances for seeing the variables that you have defined for dealing with the

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:40.540
plots that you've created.

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:44.979
For getting help right in your IDE so that you don't have to, like, kind of get out of

00:33:44.979 --> 00:33:50.540
the flow state when you need to quickly look up a, you know, a function signature or how

00:33:50.540 --> 00:33:53.699
certain method works.

00:33:53.699 --> 00:34:02.140
Our design of Positron here is directly informed by the years of experience at my company building

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:07.219
these kinds of tools for a data analyst user persona, the kind of person who deals with

00:34:07.219 --> 00:34:09.560
data on a regular basis.

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:14.179
If you have ever used VS Code, you probably also think this looks pretty familiar.

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:19.300
And that's because Positron is built on top of the open source components that are used

00:34:19.300 --> 00:34:21.500
to build Visual Studio Code.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:23.580
There are two main reasons we've done this.

00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:27.739
The first one is that it allows us to concentrate on what we're good at.

00:34:27.739 --> 00:34:32.860
Like, internally at my company, we have a lot of experience around data science tooling.

00:34:32.860 --> 00:34:39.179
And by using the general purpose components from the open source parts of VS Code, like,

00:34:39.179 --> 00:34:44.739
the, you know, support around general source code editing, saving files, interacting with

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:49.820
version control, we can focus on the, like, with a fairly smallish team, we can focus

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:56.580
on the pieces of the data science IDE that we think are table stakes and don't exist

00:34:56.580 --> 00:35:00.060
for a general purpose software engineering IDE.

00:35:00.060 --> 00:35:07.300
A second big reason is it allows us to connect into the vast ecosystem of VS Code compatible

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:08.760
extensions.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:13.000
Our studio as an IDE was never very extensible or customizable.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:17.439
And by building something that works with these extensions, we really open up people's

00:35:17.439 --> 00:35:22.840
ability to customize their IDE for the kinds of tools, the kinds of tasks that they have,

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:25.159
the kinds of things that these need to do.

00:35:25.159 --> 00:35:28.800
And in fact, we ourselves developed some of these very extensions.

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:34.239
So this is what developing a Cordo document looks like in Positron.

00:35:34.239 --> 00:35:40.639
And it uses the same VS Code compatible extension, the Cordo extension, that you would use in

00:35:40.639 --> 00:35:43.600
officially, like, Microsoft branded VS Code.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:49.199
So the extensions can be used in both places, and we're able to modularize code in ways

00:35:49.199 --> 00:35:55.600
that has really big benefits for the kind of people who do this kind of work.

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:59.560
So I am really excited about this.

00:35:59.560 --> 00:36:04.719
Like I said, like, a big reason why is because it is the project I have worked on where I

00:36:04.719 --> 00:36:11.600
have most observed this back and forth and this learning and then sharing.

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:15.639
And I don't only mean, like, from RStudio to Python.

00:36:15.639 --> 00:36:16.919
I don't only mean that.

00:36:16.919 --> 00:36:23.040
I mean learning from, like, the general software engineering, like, the way debuggers are built,

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:30.639
the way that, like, plots are, like, information about plots is shared in different kinds of tools.

00:36:30.639 --> 00:36:34.679
Like, I've observed this in a way that's really exciting for me.

00:36:34.679 --> 00:36:39.320
I want to emphasize that Positron is a very early stage project.

00:36:39.320 --> 00:36:46.399
Today is Wednesday, and it has not even been a full two weeks that this project has been public.

00:36:46.399 --> 00:36:49.360
So it is, like, a brand new baby.

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:53.040
And, boy, I love babies, but babies can be, you know, a little bit of a mess, a little

00:36:53.040 --> 00:36:54.040
bit of a challenge.

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:58.320
